This article is a presidential memorandum issued by President Barack Obama on March 19, 2015. The memorandum establishes the Director of White House Information Technology and the Executive Committee for Presidential Information Technology. The purpose of the memorandum is to improve the information resources and systems provided to the President, Vice President, and the Executive Office of the President (EOP). It aims to ensure that these resources and systems are efficient, secure, and resilient, while reducing operating costs through the elimination of duplication and overlapping services. The Director of White House Information Technology is given the authority to establish and coordinate policies and procedures for operating and maintaining these resources and systems. The memorandum also establishes the Executive Committee for Presidential Information Technology, consisting of various officials or their designees, who will advise and make policy recommendations to the Director and the Deputy Chief of Staff for Operations. The memorandum emphasizes that the President retains exclusive control over these resources and systems and does not delegate ownership or rights associated with ownership to any entity outside of the EOP. The memorandum also includes definitions and general provisions.